# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rdma-networking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rdma-networking/data-center-bridging] Ethernet is the primary network protocol in data centers for computer-to-computer communications.
[src:rdma-networking/data-center-bridging] However, Ethernet is designed to be a best-effort network that may experience packet loss when the network or devices are busy.
[src:rdma-networking/data-center-bridging] Under the end-to-end principle, transport reliability in IP networks is the responsibility of a transport protocol, such as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:rdma-networking/data-center-bridging] One area of evolution for Ethernet is to add extensions to the existing protocol suite to provide reliability without requiring the complexity of TCP.
[src:rdma-networking/data-center-bridging] With the move to 10 Gbit/s and faster transmission rates, there is also a desire for finer granularity in control of bandwidth allocation and to ensure it is used more effectively.
[src:rdma-networking/data-center-bridging] These enhancements are particularly important to make Ethernet a more viable transport for storage and server cluster traffic.
[src:rdma-networking/data-center-bridging] A primary motivation is the sensitivity of Fibre Channel over Ethernet to frame loss.
[src:rdma-networking/data-center-bridging] The higher level goal is to use a single set of Ethernet physical devices or adapters for computers to talk to a storage area network (SAN), local area network (LAN) and InfiniBand fabric.
[src:rdma-networking/data-center-bridging] DCB aims, for selected traffic, to eliminate loss due to queue overflow (sometimes called **lossless Ethernet**) and to be able to allocate bandwidth on links.
[src:rdma-networking/data-center-bridging] Essentially, DCB enables, to some extent, the treatment of different priorities as if they were different pipes.
[src:rdma-networking/data-center-bridging] To meet these goals new standards are being (or have been) developed that either extend the existing set of Ethernet protocols or emulate the connectivity offered by Ethernet protocols.
[src:rdma-networking/data-center-bridging] Enabling DCB broadly on arbitrary networks with irregular topologies and without special routing may cause deadlocks, large buffering delays, unfairness and head-of-line blocking.
[src:rdma-networking/data-center-bridging] It was suggested to use DCB to eliminate TCP slow start using the approach of **TCP-Bolt**.
[src:rdma-networking/data-center-bridging] These new protocols required new hardware and software in both the network and the network interface controller.
[src:rdma-networking/data-center-bridging] Products were being developed by companies such as Avaya, Brocade, Cisco, Dell, EMC, Emulex, HP, Huawei, IBM, and Qlogic.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] The first flow control mechanism, the **pause frame**, was defined by the **IEEE 802.3x** standard.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] A sending station (computer or network switch) may be transmitting data faster than the other end of the link can accept it.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] Using flow control, the receiving station can signal the sender requesting suspension of transmissions until the receiver catches up.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] Flow control on Ethernet can be implemented at the data link layer.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] The first flow control mechanism, the *pause frame*, was defined by the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) task force that defined full duplex Ethernet link segments.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] The IEEE standard 802.3x was issued in 1997.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] An overwhelmed network node can send a pause frame, which halts the transmission of the sender for a specified period of time.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] A media access control (MAC) frame (EtherType 0x8808) is used to carry the pause command, with the Control opcode set to 0x0001 (hexadecimal).
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] Only stations configured for full-duplex operation may send pause frames.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] When a station wishes to pause the other end of a link, it sends a pause frame to either the unique 48-bit destination address of this link or to the 48-bit reserved multicast address of 01-80-C2-00-00-01.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] The use of a well-known address makes it unnecessary for a station to discover and store the address of the station at the other end of the link.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] Another advantage of using this multicast address arises from the use of flow control between network switches.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] The particular multicast address used is selected from a range of addresses that have been reserved by the IEEE 802.1D standard, which specifies the operation of switches used for bridging.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] Normally, a frame with a multicast destination sent to a switch will be forwarded out to all other ports of the switch.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] However, this range of multicast addresses is special and will not be forwarded by an 802.1D-compliant switch.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] Instead, frames sent to this range are understood to be frames meant to be acted upon only within the switch.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] A pause frame includes the period of pause time being requested, in the form of a two-byte (16-bit), unsigned integer (0 through 65535).
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] This number is the requested duration of the pause.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] The pause time is measured in units of pause *quanta*, where each quanta is equal to 512 bit times.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] By 1999, several vendors supported receiving pause frames, but fewer implemented sending them.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] One original motivation for the pause frame was to handle network interface controllers (NICs) that did not have enough buffering to handle full-speed reception.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] This problem has become less common with advances in bus speeds and memory sizes.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] A more likely scenario is network congestion within a switch.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] For example, a flow can come into a switch on a higher speed link than the one it goes out, or several flows can come in over two or more links that total more than an output link's bandwidth.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] These will eventually exhaust any amount of buffering in the switch.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] However, blocking the sending link will cause all flows over that link to be delayed, even those that are not causing any congestion.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] This situation is a case of head-of-line (HOL) blocking, and can happen more often in core network switches due to the large numbers of flows generally being aggregated.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] Many switches use a technique called virtual output queues to eliminate the HOL blocking internally, so they will never send pause frames.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] Another effort began in March 2004, and in May 2004, it became the IEEE P802.3ar Congestion Management Task Force.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] In May 2006, the objectives of the task force were revised to specify a mechanism to limit the transmitted data rate at about 1% granularity.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] The request was withdrawn and the task force was disbanded in 2008.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] Ethernet flow control disturbs the Ethernet class of service (defined in IEEE 802.1p), as the data of all priorities is stopped to clear the existing buffers, which might also consist of low-priority data.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] As a remedy to this problem, Cisco Systems defined its own priority flow control extension to the standard protocol.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] This mechanism uses 14 bytes of the 42-byte padding in a regular pause frame.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] The MAC control opcode for a Priority pause frame is 0x0101.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] Unlike the original pause, Priority pause indicates the pause time in quanta for each of the eight priority classes separately.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] The extension was subsequently standardized by the Priority-based Flow Control (PFC) project authorized on March 27, 2008, as IEEE 802.1Qbb.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] Claudio DeSanti of Cisco was the editor.
[src:rdma-networking/ethernet-flow-control] The effort was part of the data center bridging task group, which developed Fibre Channel over Ethernet.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] Mellanox (acquired by Nvidia) manufactures InfiniBand host bus adapters and network switches, which are used by large computer system and database vendors in their product lines.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] As a computer cluster interconnect, IB competes with Ethernet, Fibre Channel, and Intel Omni-Path.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] The technology is promoted by the **InfiniBand Trade Association**.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] InfiniBand originated in 1999 from the merger of two competing designs: Future I/O and Next Generation I/O (NGIO).
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] NGIO was led by Intel, with a specification released in 1998, and joined by Sun Microsystems and Dell.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] Future I/O was backed by Compaq, IBM, and Hewlett-Packard.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] This led to the formation of the InfiniBand Trade Association (IBTA), which included both sets of hardware vendors as well as software vendors such as Microsoft.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] At the time it was thought some of the more powerful computers were approaching the interconnect bottleneck of the PCI bus, in spite of upgrades like PCI-X.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] Version 1.0 of the InfiniBand Architecture Specification was released in 2000.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] Initially the IBTA vision for IB was simultaneously a replacement for PCI in I/O, Ethernet in the machine room, cluster interconnect and Fibre Channel.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] IBTA also envisaged decomposing server hardware on an IB fabric.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] Mellanox had been founded in 1999 to develop NGIO technology, but by 2001 shipped an InfiniBand product line called InfiniBridge at 10 Gbit/second speeds.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] Following the burst of the dot-com bubble there was hesitation in the industry to invest in such a far-reaching technology jump.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] By 2002, Intel announced that instead of shipping IB integrated circuits ("chips"), it would focus on developing PCI Express, and Microsoft discontinued IB development in favor of extending Ethernet.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] Sun Microsystems and Hitachi continued to support IB.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] In 2003, the System X supercomputer built at Virginia Tech used InfiniBand in what was estimated to be the third largest computer in the world at the time.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] The OpenIB Alliance (later renamed OpenFabrics Alliance) was founded in 2004 to develop an open set of software for the Linux kernel.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] By February, 2005, the support was accepted into the 2.6.11 Linux kernel.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] In November 2005 storage devices finally were released using InfiniBand from vendors such as Engenio.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] Cisco, desiring to keep technology superior to Ethernet off the market, adopted a "buy to kill" strategy.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] Cisco successfully killed InfiniBand switching companies such as Topspin via acquisition.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] Of the top 500 supercomputers in 2009, Gigabit Ethernet was the internal interconnect technology in 259 installations, compared with 181 using InfiniBand.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] In 2010, market leaders Mellanox and Voltaire merged, leaving just one other IB vendor, QLogic, primarily a Fibre Channel vendor.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] At the 2011 International Supercomputing Conference, links running at about 56 gigabits per second (known as FDR, see below), were announced and demonstrated by connecting booths in the trade show.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] In 2012, Intel acquired QLogic's InfiniBand technology, leaving only one independent supplier.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] By 2014, InfiniBand was the most popular internal connection technology for supercomputers, although within two years, 10 Gigabit Ethernet started displacing it.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] In 2016, it was reported that Oracle Corporation (an investor in Mellanox) might engineer its own InfiniBand hardware.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] In 2019 Nvidia acquired Mellanox, the last independent supplier of InfiniBand products.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] Specifications are published by the InfiniBand trade association.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] Original names for speeds were single-data rate (SDR), double-data rate (DDR) and quad-data rate (QDR) as given below.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] Subsequently, other three-letter initialisms were added for even higher data rates.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] Links can be aggregated: most systems use a 4 link/lane connector (QSFP).
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] HDR often makes use of 2x links (aka HDR100, 100 Gb link using 2 lanes of HDR, while still using a QSFP connector).
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] NDR introduced OSFP connectors which host one or two links at 2x (NDR200) or 4x (NDR400).
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] They are not logically configured as a single 8x link, even when connecting switches together with an OSFP cable.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] InfiniBand provides remote direct memory access (RDMA) capabilities for low CPU overhead.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] InfiniBand uses a switched fabric topology, as opposed to early shared medium Ethernet.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] All transmissions begin or end at a channel adapter.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] Each processor contains a host channel adapter (HCA) and each peripheral has a target channel adapter (TCA).
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] These adapters can also exchange information for security or quality of service (QoS).
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] InfiniBand transmits data in packets of up to 4 KB that are taken together to form a message.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] In addition to a board form factor connection, it can use both active and passive copper (up to 10 meters) and optical fiber cable (up to 10 km).
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] The InfiniBand Association also specified the CXP connector system for speeds up to 120 Gbit/s over copper, active optical cables, and optical transceivers using parallel multi-mode fiber cables with 24-fiber MPO connectors.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] Mellanox operating system support is available for Solaris, FreeBSD, Red Hat Enterprise Linux, SUSE Linux Enterprise Server (SLES), Windows, HP-UX, VMware ESX, and AIX.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] InfiniBand has no specific standard application programming interface (API).
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] The standard only lists a set of verbs such as `ibv_open_device` or `ibv_post_send`, which are abstract representations of functions or methods that must exist.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] The syntax of these functions is left to the vendors.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] Sometimes for reference this is called the *verbs* API.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] The de facto standard software is developed by OpenFabrics Alliance and called the Open Fabrics Enterprise Distribution (OFED).
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] It is released under two licenses GPL2 or BSD license for Linux and FreeBSD, and as Mellanox OFED for Windows (product names: WinOF / WinOF-2; attributed as host controller driver for matching specific ConnectX 3 to 5 devices) under a choice of BSD license for Windows.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] It has been adopted by most of the InfiniBand vendors, for Linux, FreeBSD, and Microsoft Windows.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] IBM refers to a software library called `libibverbs`, for its AIX operating system, as well as "AIX InfiniBand verbs".
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] The Linux kernel support was integrated in 2005 into the kernel version 2.6.11.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] Ethernet over InfiniBand, abbreviated to EoIB, is an Ethernet implementation over the InfiniBand protocol and connector technology.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] EoIB enables multiple Ethernet bandwidths varying on the InfiniBand (IB) version.
[src:rdma-networking/infiniband] Ethernet's implementation of the Internet Protocol Suite, usually referred to as TCP/IP, is different in some details compared to the direct InfiniBand protocol in IP over IB (IPoIB).
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] There are many different ways to measure the performance of a network, as each network is different in nature and design.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] Performance can also be modeled and simulated instead of measured; one example of this is using state transition diagrams to model queuing performance or to use a Network Simulator.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] The available channel bandwidth and achievable signal-to-noise ratio determine the maximum possible throughput.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] It is not generally possible to send more data than dictated by the Shannon-Hartley Theorem.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] The *Time Window* is the period over which the throughput is measured.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] The choice of an appropriate time window will often dominate calculations of throughput, and whether latency is taken into account or not will determine whether the latency affects the throughput or not.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] The speed of light imposes a minimum propagation time on all electromagnetic signals.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] where s is the distance and cm is the speed of light in the medium (roughly 200,000 km/s for most fiber or electrical media, depending on their velocity factor).
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] This approximately means an additional millisecond round-trip delay (RTT) per 100 km (or 62 miles) of distance between hosts.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] Other delays also occur in intermediate nodes.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] In packet switched networks delays can occur due to queueing.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] In digital transmission, the number of **bit errors** is the number of received bits of a data stream over a communication channel that have been altered due to noise, interference, distortion or bit synchronization errors.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] The **bit error rate** or **bit error ratio** (**BER**) is the number of bit errors divided by the total number of transferred bits during a studied time interval.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] BER is a unitless performance measure, often expressed as a percentage.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] The **bit error probability** *pe* is the expectation value of the BER.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] The BER can be considered as an approximate estimate of the bit error probability.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] This estimate is accurate for a long time interval and a high number of bit errors.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] All of the factors above, coupled with user requirements and user perceptions, play a role in determining the perceived 'fastness' or utility, of a network connection.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] The relationship between throughput, latency, and user experience is most aptly understood in the context of a shared network medium, and as a scheduling problem.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] For some systems, latency and throughput are coupled entities.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] In TCP/IP, latency can also directly affect throughput.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] In TCP connections, the large bandwidth-delay product of high latency connections, combined with relatively small TCP window sizes on many devices, effectively causes the throughput of a high latency connection to drop sharply with latency.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] This can be remedied with various techniques, such as increasing the TCP congestion window size, or more drastic solutions, such as packet coalescing, TCP acceleration, and forward error correction, all of which are commonly used for high latency satellite links.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] TCP acceleration converts the TCP packets into a stream that is similar to UDP.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] Because of this, the TCP acceleration software must provide its own mechanisms to ensure the reliability of the link, taking the latency and bandwidth of the link into account, and both ends of the high latency link must support the method used.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] In the Media Access Control (MAC) layer, performance issues such as throughput and end-to-end delay are also addressed.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] Many systems can be characterized as dominated either by throughput limitations or by latency limitations in terms of end-user utility or experience.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] In some cases, hard limits such as the speed of light present unique problems to such systems and nothing can be done to correct this.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] Other systems allow for significant balancing and optimization for best user experience.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] A telecom satellite in geosynchronous orbit imposes a path length of at least 71000 km between transmitter and receiver. which means a minimum delay between message request and message receipt, or latency of 473 ms.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] This delay can be very noticeable and affects satellite phone service regardless of available throughput capacity.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] These long path length considerations are exacerbated when communicating with space probes and other long-range targets beyond Earth's atmosphere.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] The Deep Space Network implemented by NASA is one such system that must cope with these problems.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] Largely latency driven, the GAO has criticized the current architecture.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] Several different methods have been proposed to handle the intermittent connectivity and long delays between packets, such as delay-tolerant networking.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] At interstellar distances, the difficulties in designing radio systems that can achieve any throughput at all are massive.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] In these cases, maintaining communication is a bigger issue than how long that communication takes.
[src:rdma-networking/network-performance] Transportation is concerned almost entirely with throughput, which is why physical deliveries of backup tape archives are still largely done by vehicle.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] Network-intensive applications like networked storage or cluster computing need a network infrastructure with a high bandwidth and low latency.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] The advantages of RDMA over other network application programming interfaces such as Berkeley sockets are lower latency, lower CPU load and higher bandwidth.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] The RoCE protocol allows lower latencies than its predecessor, the iWARP protocol.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] There are RoCE HCAs (Host Channel Adapter) with a latency as low as 1.3 microseconds while the lowest known iWARP HCA latency in 2011 was 3 microseconds.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] RoCE versions differ in Layers 3 through Layer 4 of the OSI model.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] All versions of RoCE support RDMA functionality via the same underlying InfiniBand messages.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] These messages exist within the Base Transport Header (BTH), Extended Transport Header, (ETH) and payload, followed by an invariant cyclic redundancy check used for data integrity.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] The RoCE v1 protocol is an Ethernet link layer protocol with Ethertype 0x8915.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] This means that the frame length limits of the Ethernet protocol apply: 1500 bytes for a regular Ethernet frame and 9000 bytes for a jumbo frame.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] The RoCE v1.5 is an uncommon, experimental, non-standardized protocol that is based on the IP protocol.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] RoCE v1.5 uses the IP protocol field to differentiate its traffic from other IP protocols such as TCP and UDP.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] The value used for the protocol number is unspecified and is left to the deployment to select.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] The RoCE v2 protocol exists on top of either the UDP/IPv4 or the UDP/IPv6 protocol.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] The UDP destination port number 4791 has been reserved for RoCE v2.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] Since RoCE v2 packets are routable the RoCE v2 protocol is sometimes called Routable RoCE or RRoCE.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] Although in general the delivery order of UDP packets is not guaranteed, the RoCE v2 specification requires that packets with the same UDP source port and the same destination address must not be reordered.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] In addition, RoCE v2 defines a congestion control mechanism that uses the IP ECN bits for marking and CNP frames for the acknowledgment notification.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] Software support for RoCE v2 is still emerging.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] Mellanox OFED 2.3 or later has RoCE v2 support and also Linux Kernel v4.5.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] Both InfiniBand and RoCE are comprehensive network standards, not an individual protocol.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] However, InfiniBand specifies the transport layer, as the 'InfiniBand Transport Layer', which RoCE also makes use of.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] This can lead to confusion between the two standards, as RoCE implements the uppermost layers of InfiniBand but not the rest of the architecture.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] RoCE defines how to perform RDMA over Ethernet while the InfiniBand architecture specification defines how to perform RDMA over an InfiniBand network.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] RoCE was expected to bring InfiniBand applications, which are predominantly based on clusters, onto a common Ethernet converged fabric.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] Others expected that InfiniBand will keep offering a higher bandwidth and lower latency than what is possible over Ethernet.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] While the RoCE protocols define how to perform RDMA using Ethernet and UDP/IP frames, the iWARP protocol defines how to perform RDMA over a connection-oriented transport like the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] RoCE v1 is limited to a single Ethernet broadcast domain.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] The memory requirements of a large number of connections along with TCP's flow and reliability controls lead to scalability and performance issues when using iWARP in large-scale datacenters and for large-scale applications (i.e., large-scale enterprises, cloud computing, web 2.0 applications etc.).
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] Also, multicast is defined in the RoCE specification while the current iWARP specification does not define how to perform multicast RDMA.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] Reliability in iWARP is given by the protocol itself, as TCP is reliable.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] RoCE v2 on the other hand utilizes UDP which has a far smaller overhead and better performance but does not provide inherent reliability, and therefore reliability must be implemented alongside RoCE v2.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] One solution is to use converged Ethernet switches to make the local area network reliable.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] This requires converged Ethernet support on all the switches in the local area network and prevents RoCE v2 packets from traveling through a wide area network such as the internet which is not reliable.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] Another solution is to add reliability to the RoCE protocol (i.e., reliable RoCE) which adds handshaking to RoCE to provide reliability at the cost of performance.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] The question of which protocol is better depends on the vendor.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] Chelsio recommends and exclusively support iWARP.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] Mellanox, Xilinx, and Broadcom recommend and exclusively support RoCE/RoCE v2.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] Intel initially supported iWARP but now supports both iWARP and RoCE v2.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] Other vendors involved in the network industry provide support for both protocols such as Marvell, Microsoft, Linux and Kazan.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] Cisco supports both RoCE and their own VIC RDMA protocol.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] Both Protocols are standardized with iWARP being the standard for RDMA over TCP defined by the IETF and RoCE being the standard for RDMA over Ethernet defined by the IBTA.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] Some aspects that could have been defined in the RoCE specification have been left out.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] In addition, any protocol running over IP cannot assume the underlying network has guaranteed ordering, any more than it can assume congestion cannot occur.
[src:rdma-networking/rdma-over-converged-ethernet] It is known that the use of PFC can lead to a network-wide deadlock.
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] In computing, **remote direct memory access** (**RDMA**) is direct memory access from the memory of one computer into that of another without involving either computer's operating system.
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] This permits high-throughput, low-latency memory access over a network, which is especially useful in massively parallel computer clusters.
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] RDMA supports zero-copy networking by enabling the network adapter to transfer data from the wire directly to application memory or from application memory directly to the wire, eliminating the need to copy data between application memory and the data buffers in the operating system.
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] Such transfers require no work to be done by CPUs, caches, or context switches, and transfers continue in parallel with other system operations.
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] This reduces latency in message transfer.
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] However, this strategy presents several problems related to the fact that the target node is not notified of the completion of the request (single-sided communications).
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] As of 2018 RDMA had achieved broader acceptance as a result of implementation enhancements that enable good performance over ordinary networking infrastructure.
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] For example RDMA over Converged Ethernet (RoCE) now is able to run over either lossy or lossless infrastructure.
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] In addition iWARP enables an Ethernet RDMA implementation at the physical layer using TCP/IP as the transport, combining the performance and latency advantages of RDMA with a low-cost, standards-based solution.
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] The RDMA Consortium and the DAT Collaborative have played key roles in the development of RDMA protocols and APIs for consideration by standards groups such as the Internet Engineering Task Force and the Interconnect Software Consortium.
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] Hardware vendors have started working on higher-capacity RDMA-based network adapters, with rates of 100 Gbit/s reported.
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] Software vendors, such as IBM, Red Hat and Oracle Corporation, support these APIs in their latest products, and since 2013, engineers have been developing network adapters that implement RDMA over Ethernet.
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] Both Red Hat Enterprise Linux and Red Hat Enterprise MRG have support for RDMA.
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] Microsoft supports RDMA in Windows Server 2012 via SMB Direct.
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] VMware ESXi also supports RDMA as of 2015.
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] Common RDMA implementations include the Virtual Interface Architecture, RDMA over Converged Ethernet (RoCE), InfiniBand, Omni-Path, iWARP and Ultra Ethernet.
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] Applications access control structures using well-defined APIs originally designed for the InfiniBand Protocol (although the APIs can be used for any of the underlying RDMA implementations).
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] Using send and completion queues, applications perform RDMA operations by submitting work queue entries (WQEs) into the submission queue (SQ) and getting notified of responses from the completion queue (CQ).
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] RDMA can transport data reliably or unreliably over the Reliably Connected (RC) and Unreliable Datagram (UD) transport protocols, respectively.
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] The former has the benefit of preserving requests (no requests are lost), while the latter requires fewer queue pairs when handling multiple connections.
[src:rdma-networking/remote-direct-memory-access] This is due to the fact that UD is connection-less, allowing a single host to communicate with any other using a single queue.
